Goodness.

1048
00:55:13,620 --> 00:55:16,150
If someone works in front, someone works in the back.

1049
00:55:16,620 --> 00:55:18,549
That's how the world works, and so is the kitchen.

1050
00:55:18,550 --> 00:55:20,420
I did my best for the team.

1051
00:55:20,960 --> 00:55:23,829
Chef Seung Geun managed to get some sugar...

1052
00:55:23,830 --> 00:55:25,830
very quickly.

1053
00:55:26,060 --> 00:55:27,500
I was very relieved.

1054
00:55:32,700 --> 00:55:35,400
- He's on the same team, right? - Yes.

1055
00:55:35,670 --> 00:55:36,810
He doesn't know.

1056
00:55:41,110 --> 00:55:42,640
For other teams,

1057
00:55:43,610 --> 00:55:47,480
I can see them working together to make the pastry.

1058
00:55:48,050 --> 00:55:49,120
Each team.

1059
00:55:49,420 --> 00:55:51,320
But for Team Six,

1060
00:55:53,120 --> 00:55:55,259
"I'll make this pastry from the start to the end."

1061
00:55:55,260 --> 00:55:56,959
"I'll make this pastry from the start to the end."

1062
00:55:56,960 --> 00:55:58,589
They're each in charge of different things.

1063
00:55:58,590 --> 00:56:01,400
The pastries might end up in their individual styles.

1064
00:56:01,930 --> 00:56:03,329
- The teamwork... - They might not work well...

1065
00:56:03,330 --> 00:56:04,469
- as a team. - Yes, teamwork...

1066
00:56:04,470 --> 00:56:05,630
- There's no teamwork. - They have three products.

1067
00:56:05,930 --> 00:56:07,600
One person might be sidelined.

1068
00:56:08,300 --> 00:56:09,940
- You're right. - Yes.

1069
00:56:11,770 --> 00:56:14,110
- Hello. - Hello.

1070
00:56:14,340 --> 00:56:16,580
- Do you have any issues? - No, we don't.

1071
00:56:17,380 --> 00:56:20,480
How's the teamwork with your teammates?

1072
00:56:20,650 --> 00:56:21,979
It's perfect.

1073
00:56:21,980 --> 00:56:24,649
Since they're all very experienced,

1074
00:56:24,650 --> 00:56:26,420
they do their tasks smoothly.

1075
00:56:28,020 --> 00:56:29,359
How about you, Natural Man?

1076
00:56:29,360 --> 00:56:32,629
Are you using any natural ingredients today?

1077
00:56:32,630 --> 00:56:34,030
No, I'm not.

1078
00:56:34,500 --> 00:56:35,699
- Not today? - You're not using one today?

1079
00:56:35,700 --> 00:56:37,530
- No. - You can't express your style.

1080
00:56:37,700 --> 00:56:38,730
I guess.

1081
00:56:40,400 --> 00:56:41,800
It's a shame.

1082
00:56:42,170 --> 00:56:44,009
It's okay. We're a team,

1083
00:56:44,010 --> 00:56:45,170
so I trust them.

1084
00:56:47,280 --> 00:56:49,110
What's your role today?

1085
00:56:50,150 --> 00:56:51,449
I'm in charge of the chores.

1086
00:56:51,450 --> 00:56:52,550
- The chores? - Yes.

1087
00:56:55,880 --> 00:56:58,520
If you don't place 1st or 2nd,

1088
00:56:58,650 --> 00:57:00,959
those in charge of chores...

1089
00:57:00,960 --> 00:57:03,020
are at a disadvantage in terms of survival.

1090
00:57:03,960 --> 00:57:07,529
Actually, he called it chores...

1091
00:57:07,530 --> 00:57:08,859
because he's being humble,

1092
00:57:08,860 --> 00:57:11,169
but it's not. From the start,

1093
00:57:11,170 --> 00:57:12,729
he was in charge...

1094
00:57:12,730 --> 00:57:15,400
of preparing everything.

1095
00:57:15,900 --> 00:57:17,970
You can't call it a chore.

1096
00:57:18,140 --> 00:57:19,509
I'm in charge of the chores.

1097
00:57:19,510 --> 00:57:20,710
- The chores? - Yes.

1098
00:57:23,980 --> 00:57:25,079
- I look forward to it. - Okay.

1099
00:57:25,080 --> 00:57:26,350
- Thank you. - Good luck.

1100
00:57:28,050 --> 00:57:31,890
I think Contender Oh Seung Geun...

1101
00:57:31,950 --> 00:57:35,190
showed consideration for others.

1102
00:57:35,560 --> 00:57:36,560
I see.

1103
00:57:36,561 --> 00:57:38,030
I was looking forward to his pastry.

1104
00:57:41,460 --> 00:57:44,200
You have 2 hours and 30 minutes left.

1105
00:57:44,900 --> 00:57:45,970
That startled me.

1106
00:57:49,570 --> 00:57:50,770
We have 2 hours and 30 minutes left.

1107
00:57:52,970 --> 00:57:54,110
We don't have much time left.

1108
00:57:54,810 --> 00:57:55,909
It'll open very soon.

1109
00:57:55,910 --> 00:57:58,209
If they mess up from here onward, it's safe to say they failed.

1110
00:57:58,210 --> 00:57:59,250
I agree.

1111
00:58:12,490 --> 00:58:13,830
We might need to redo the dough.

1112
00:58:13,960 --> 00:58:15,430
Let's do it quickly.

1113
00:58:16,560 --> 00:58:17,800
The choux isn't ready?

1114
00:58:20,970 --> 00:58:22,600
It's game over if they don't have the choux.

1115
00:58:23,710 --> 00:58:24,769
No.

1116
00:58:24,770 --> 00:58:26,609
- We have to redo it, right? - Yes. This won't work.

1117
00:58:26,610 --> 00:58:28,410
It didn't turn out right. This is sable.

1118
00:58:29,280 --> 00:58:31,050
What will Team Three do?

1119
00:58:31,810 --> 00:58:33,149
I'll quickly make choux pastry.

1120
00:58:33,150 --> 00:58:34,880
Don't think too hard. I'll redo choux pastry.

1121
00:58:35,120 --> 00:58:36,889
Quite a lot of time had passed.

1122
00:58:36,890 --> 00:58:39,689
If the dough fails again,

1123
00:58:39,690 --> 00:58:42,619
it's really over.

1124
00:58:42,620 --> 00:58:45,659
Nobody said it out loud,

1125
00:58:45,660 --> 00:58:49,030
but I think everyone was nervous and sensitive then.

1126
00:58:52,230 --> 00:58:55,800
First, do we have enough flour and eggs to make two trays?

1127
00:58:55,970 --> 00:58:57,010
Yes.

1128
00:58:58,070 --> 00:59:00,340
We don't need many eggs to make the dough.

1129
00:59:00,810 --> 00:59:02,980
- We can make 2.5 times... - Don't just say that.

1130
00:59:03,280 --> 00:59:05,450
Write down exactly how much we need.

1131
00:59:05,910 --> 00:59:09,220
If we do that, we can make two and a half trays.

1132
00:59:09,350 --> 00:59:10,490
Then let's redo it.

1133
00:59:10,590 --> 00:59:11,850
We'll redo it, and split up the two.

1134
00:59:13,050 --> 00:59:15,559
Honestly, we thought there was a problem with the dough,

1135
00:59:15,560 --> 00:59:17,589
but we didn't have enough ingredients...

1136
00:59:17,590 --> 00:59:19,160
for the last tray.

1137
00:59:19,590 --> 00:59:21,600
What about Chou-umami? Shouldn't we redo it too?

1138
00:59:21,960 --> 00:59:23,929
- We don't have enough eggs for it. - No.

1139
00:59:23,930 --> 00:59:25,070
Then we shouldn't think about it.

1140
00:59:30,270 --> 00:59:31,370
No.

1141
00:59:31,970 --> 00:59:33,210
Let's set this quickly.

1142
00:59:33,610 --> 00:59:35,179
Everyone work on making the choux pastry.

1143
00:59:35,180 --> 00:59:37,250
- Without it, we can't do anything. - That's right.

1144
00:59:39,080 --> 00:59:40,380
Okay, I'll...

1145
00:59:43,280 --> 00:59:44,319
"What to do?"

1146
00:59:44,320 --> 00:59:46,250
"Can we make this work?"

1147
00:59:48,860 --> 00:59:52,629
I kept making one mistake after another,

1148
00:59:52,630 --> 00:59:54,800
so I was making it in panic.

1149
00:59:56,700 --> 00:59:59,030
Since this is the final chance, we should do well.

1150
01:00:10,450 --> 01:00:13,679
Actually, you don't work on such a large quantity manually.

1151
01:00:13,680 --> 01:00:15,380
Most people use machines.

1152
01:00:15,550 --> 01:00:18,050
But we wasted almost one hour.

1153
01:00:18,450 --> 01:00:21,560
Let's just do it manually and use our hands.

1154
01:00:22,260 --> 01:00:25,659
So two of us mixed it with our hands.

1155
01:00:25,660 --> 01:00:27,530
We threw away the dough we made previously.

1156
01:00:31,770 --> 01:00:33,430
I had zero thought. I should just work on it quickly.

1157
01:00:33,700 --> 01:00:34,970
I should make it work no matter what.

1158
01:00:42,080 --> 01:00:43,910
I'll force it through. Hand it over.

1159
01:00:44,150 --> 01:00:45,350
I'll just use force.

1160
01:00:54,860 --> 01:00:55,960
Please.

1161
01:00:56,290 --> 01:00:59,090
Team Dopamine Day, stay strong.

1162
01:01:14,140 --> 01:01:15,980
It's hot. I'm sweating.

1163
01:01:16,940 --> 01:01:18,650
We'll start plating after 30 minutes.

1164
01:01:19,750 --> 01:01:22,150
- Let's do it. - Let's do it.

1165
01:01:24,020 --> 01:01:25,550
I think...

1166
01:01:25,990 --> 01:01:27,690
What happened to the choux pastry?

1167
01:01:28,920 --> 01:01:30,729
- This will work. - It looks dense enough.

1168
01:01:30,730 --> 01:01:32,829
- Okay. From the gloss alone... - This looks right.

1169
01:01:32,830 --> 01:01:33,860
This is it.

1170
01:01:34,600 --> 01:01:35,760
This is the density I want.

1171
01:01:37,630 --> 01:01:39,970
- Thank goodness. - I'm so glad.

1172
01:01:40,270 --> 01:01:41,600
- I know, right? - I'm so glad.

1173
01:01:45,770 --> 01:01:47,810
The sky hasn't abandoned us yet.

1174
01:01:48,940 --> 01:01:50,180
I breathed in relief.

1175
01:01:51,480 --> 01:01:53,710
I worked on the choux six times.

1176
01:01:55,250 --> 01:01:57,850
It was supposed to be three times.

1177
01:02:00,690 --> 01:02:02,720
Let's laugh a bit later.

1178
01:02:03,890 --> 01:02:06,059
I don't think the situation calls for laughs.

1179
01:02:06,060 --> 01:02:07,060
All right.

1180
01:02:07,260 --> 01:02:09,700
It wasn't what we expected. It was actually embarrassing.

1181
01:02:18,770 --> 01:02:21,240
It's coming out. The choux is coming out.

1182
01:02:39,130 --> 01:02:40,260
Nice.

1183
01:02:40,930 --> 01:02:42,130
Nice.

1184
01:02:42,900 --> 01:02:45,930
It's going to be okay. Thank goodness.

1185
01:02:46,300 --> 01:02:48,870
I'm glad we were able to make that happen.

1186
01:02:48,940 --> 01:02:50,640
- Me too. - We are not that stupid.

1187
01:02:53,140 --> 01:02:54,140
Gosh.

1188
01:02:55,740 --> 01:02:56,980
It was an experience.

1189
01:02:57,480 --> 01:02:58,480
A good experience.

1190
01:02:58,950 --> 01:03:01,220
This is our indomitable choux.

1191
01:03:02,820 --> 01:03:04,890
Will you make choux again in the following competitions?

1192
01:03:06,990 --> 01:03:08,689
There won't be choux ever again.

1193
01:03:08,690 --> 01:03:09,760
No.

1194
01:03:09,820 --> 01:03:10,960
Of course not.

1195
01:03:12,660 --> 01:03:15,529
But the Masters might not be happy with them.

1196
01:03:15,530 --> 01:03:17,770
"Do you call this a choux?"

1197
01:03:18,230 --> 01:03:19,400
"Are you sure you know how to make one?"

1198
01:03:20,700 --> 01:03:22,570
- That's what she'll say. - She sounds angry.

1199
01:03:24,170 --> 01:03:25,310
"What is this? Chinese flower bun?"

1200
01:03:26,970 --> 01:03:28,610
Everyone's spirits are back up.

1201
01:03:28,680 --> 01:03:30,309
- How funny. - We have to focus.

1202
01:03:30,310 --> 01:03:31,510
Yes, we must focus.

1203
01:03:31,780 --> 01:03:33,549
You can talk, but your hands must not rest.

1204
01:03:33,550 --> 01:03:34,979
- Don't move your mouth. - Focus.

1205
01:03:34,980 --> 01:03:36,520
- All right. Focus. - Focus.

1206
01:03:46,530 --> 01:03:48,330
We have 40 minutes until wrap.

1207
01:03:48,660 --> 01:03:49,730
Let's do this.

1208
01:03:50,160 --> 01:03:51,170
Come on.

1209
01:03:51,430 --> 01:03:53,330
Let's focus until the very end.

1210
01:03:55,870 --> 01:03:56,870
How pretty.

1211
01:03:56,871 --> 01:03:58,069
It looks better than expected, right?

1212
01:03:58,070 --> 01:03:59,540
- Absolutely. - Yes.

1213
01:04:00,240 --> 01:04:02,739
Team Dopamine Day used...

1214
01:04:02,740 --> 01:04:05,449
the classic choux dough....

1215
01:04:05,450 --> 01:04:07,050
to make three kinds of desserts.

1216
01:04:12,050 --> 01:04:14,820
This one uses cheese among other tasty ingredients.

1217
01:04:14,860 --> 01:04:15,860
This is Chou-umami.

1218
01:04:16,260 --> 01:04:18,489
This one is a parody of an ice cream flavor.

1219
01:04:18,490 --> 01:04:20,330
This is Chou-ting Star.

1220
01:04:20,490 --> 01:04:22,359
The last one...

1221
01:04:22,360 --> 01:04:25,130
was made with caramel and matcha.

1222
01:04:25,270 --> 01:04:26,970
This is Chou-dal.

1223
01:04:30,870 --> 01:04:33,570
- She's trying to grind seeds. - Sesame seeds.

1224
01:04:33,740 --> 01:04:36,509
Don't they add ground sesame seeds to gamjatang?

1225
01:04:36,510 --> 01:04:39,180
- Perilla seed powder. - Yes. Perilla seed powder.

1226
01:04:45,320 --> 01:04:47,260
- They're so detailed. - Exactly.

1227
01:04:47,520 --> 01:04:49,919
If their bread tastes good, it's over.

1228
01:04:49,920 --> 01:04:50,929
They'll be in first place for sure.

1229
01:04:50,930 --> 01:04:52,230
I want to start a business with them.

1230
01:04:57,870 --> 01:04:59,830
Their dough is black.

1231
01:05:02,070 --> 01:05:03,700
Did they use squid ink again?

1232
01:05:10,580 --> 01:05:13,450
I'll take whatever is done first.

1233
01:05:13,550 --> 01:05:15,650
- It's Team Hangover Day. - Right.

1234
01:05:15,850 --> 01:05:18,289
They're trying to make black bread.

1235
01:05:18,290 --> 01:05:20,960
Are they making a ttukbaegi which holds the gamjatang?

1236
01:05:21,090 --> 01:05:22,119
Ttukbaegi bread?

1237
01:05:22,120 --> 01:05:23,659
Yes. Gamjatang comes out boiling...

1238
01:05:23,660 --> 01:05:26,189
in a ttukbaegi. Maybe they're making a ttubaegi...

1239
01:05:26,190 --> 01:05:27,800
- to recreate it. - That would be cool.

1240
01:05:28,030 --> 01:05:29,700
I'm very excited for it.

1241
01:05:29,830 --> 01:05:32,700
We made ttukbaegi too. It's like our base.

1242
01:05:33,730 --> 01:05:36,069
Even if it is round like a bread,

1243
01:05:36,070 --> 01:05:38,670
it can feel like a ttukbaegi if we put something on top.

1244
01:05:40,370 --> 01:05:42,680
But the ttukbaegi base...

1245
01:05:43,180 --> 01:05:44,650
is a delicious cookie too.

1246
01:05:49,450 --> 01:05:52,090
Did they make a mold in just two weeks?

1247
01:05:52,490 --> 01:05:53,690
- What a great idea. - Ttukbaegi.

1248
01:05:54,760 --> 01:05:57,459
We had to make 170 cookies...

1249
01:05:57,460 --> 01:05:59,660
because they break easily.

1250
01:06:05,170 --> 01:06:06,530
I'm not strong enough.

1251
01:06:06,630 --> 01:06:07,839
- Do you want me to do it? - No.

1252
01:06:07,840 --> 01:06:09,199
I'll just make more trips.

1253
01:06:09,200 --> 01:06:10,300
Take your time.

1254
01:06:11,310 --> 01:06:14,080
- When we roll them out, - Yes?

1255
01:06:14,380 --> 01:06:17,039
we'll work on the colder ones first.

1256
01:06:17,040 --> 01:06:18,080
Okay.

1257
01:06:47,310 --> 01:06:51,409
Each sheet only produces 6 to 7 bases.

1258
01:06:51,410 --> 01:06:53,910
In order to get 160 of them...

1259
01:06:58,150 --> 01:06:59,150
When do you expect to finish?

1260
01:07:00,420 --> 01:07:02,059
- I'm done now. - I need you to help cut.

1261
01:07:02,060 --> 01:07:04,090
I'll roll out the dough and put them in the refrigerator.

1262
01:07:04,790 --> 01:07:05,790
Okay.

1263
01:07:11,100 --> 01:07:12,230
Gosh.

1264
01:07:12,400 --> 01:07:14,239
Every single step takes effort.

1265
01:07:14,240 --> 01:07:16,039
- It takes a lot of work. - It sure does.

1266
01:07:16,040 --> 01:07:17,869
We just enjoy them without thinking.

1267
01:07:17,870 --> 01:07:19,109
- But while watching them, - Yes.

1268
01:07:19,110 --> 01:07:21,239
I realize how much work goes into it.

1269
01:07:21,240 --> 01:07:23,439
I thought pretty desserts were just pretty.

1270
01:07:23,440 --> 01:07:24,580
There was more to it.

1271
01:07:31,250 --> 01:07:33,020
- Did you move the cookies? - What?

1272
01:07:33,320 --> 01:07:35,090
- No. - It's not in the refrigerator.

1273
01:07:35,690 --> 01:07:36,960
- What? - Were they moved?

1274
01:07:37,190 --> 01:07:38,760
- Did you move them? - No.

1275
01:07:44,770 --> 01:07:45,770
Cookie.

1276
01:07:46,770 --> 01:07:49,170
Cookie. Did you move the rolled-out dough?

1277
01:07:49,440 --> 01:07:50,810
- Yes. - They're over there.

1278
01:07:51,210 --> 01:07:53,710
- Where? - Not this. Rolled-out ones.

1279
01:07:54,740 --> 01:07:56,909
Didn't you ask me to knead the rolled-out dough?

1280
01:07:56,910 --> 01:07:58,650
Didn't you ask me to knead the rolled-out dough?

1281
01:07:59,010 --> 01:08:01,750
There's cookie dough in the freezer. Can you loosen it out?

1282
01:08:03,780 --> 01:08:07,519
- We have to use the mold. - Just loosen it out for backup.

1283
01:08:07,520 --> 01:08:08,590
Okay.

1284
01:08:16,160 --> 01:08:17,360
Where is the perilla oil?

1285
01:08:21,370 --> 01:08:22,600
I need minced garlic and perilla oil.

1286
01:08:41,360 --> 01:08:43,559
Chef Lee Kyung Mu had rolled out the dough,

1287
01:08:43,560 --> 01:08:45,230
and it just had to be cut.

1288
01:08:48,960 --> 01:08:51,869
I thought we had to loosen the dough,

1289
01:08:51,870 --> 01:08:53,800
so I ended up kneading it.

1290
01:08:54,600 --> 01:08:56,700
Didn't you ask me to knead the rolled-out dough?

1291
01:08:57,710 --> 01:09:00,140
Did you knead the rolled-out dough?

1292
01:09:00,470 --> 01:09:02,440
That was when...

1293
01:09:02,540 --> 01:09:03,740
I had a mental breakdown.

1294
01:09:04,310 --> 01:09:06,910
- Really? I misunderstood. - Yes.

1295
01:09:07,410 --> 01:09:10,320
It was impossible to amend.

1296
01:09:11,150 --> 01:09:15,860
I couldn't express how sorry I felt.

1297
01:09:17,690 --> 01:09:18,760
It has to be rolled out again, right?

1298
01:09:19,430 --> 01:09:20,690
- I'll take it away. - Okay.

1299
01:09:21,330 --> 01:09:22,899
This makes things complicated.

1300
01:09:22,900 --> 01:09:24,800
We were tight on time, and we had a lot to make.

1301
01:09:25,770 --> 01:09:28,639
We had a perfectly timed schedule.

1302
01:09:28,640 --> 01:09:32,110
Each job had to be done at a specific time by the assigned.

1303
01:09:32,640 --> 01:09:34,840
But this incident had reset everything.

1304
01:09:37,810 --> 01:09:39,650
No.

1305
01:09:44,120 --> 01:09:45,390
